 offers a social space where participants can prove their talents, resolve, and moral worth. Working across social theory, phenomenology, Indian metaphysics, and psychoanalysis, Singh shows that the pilgrimage provides a place in which participants can simultaneously recreate and prepare for the poor, informal economy and inevitable social uncertainties. In identifying with Śiva, who is both Master of the World and yet a pathetic drunkard, participants demonstrate their own sovereignty and desirability despite their stigmatized status. Uprising of the Fools shows how religion today is not a retreat into tradition, but an alternative forum for recognition and resistance within a rampant global neoliberalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aCapitalismxMoral and ethical aspectsxIndia. 0aCapitalismxMoral and ethical aspectszIndia. 0aHindu pilgrims and pilgrimagesxIndiaxHaridwār. 0aHindu pilgrims and pilgrimageszIndiazHaridwār. 0aHindu pilgrims and pilgrimageszIndiazHaridwār. 0aReligion and social statusxIndia. 0aReligion and social statuszIndia. 4acare. 4aethics. 4aethnography. 4amythology. 4aneo-liberalism. 4apsychoanalysis. 4arecognition. 4areligion. 4aresistance. 4aŚiva. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Classes & Economic Disparity.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360174140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503601741423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503601741.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles